<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-199-203 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 507 456</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  March 18 1991 n312 p24(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MIS offensive: data center shield: how are IS execs protectingtheir organizations against the possibility of attack?andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Some interesting responses to a survey regarding data centersecurity offer some insight into the ways executives think abouttheir information resources.andP;  One respondent revealed that hisbuilding was across the street from a Federal Court House,prompting concern that it may be used as a sniping location.andO;Users are being involved in security planning and companies arestoring backups at other sites.andP;  Others have enhanced perimetersecurity and conducted employee awareness programs.andP;  Data Centerfacility signs have been removed from building directories.andP;  Therecession and budgetary constraints have taken care of personneland travel policies.andP;  Ensuring data security means, to variousrespondents, winning the war, not opening offices abroad, creatingoff-site backups, formulating contingency plans.andP;  Also importantare vigilance and being discrete about talking about computerfacilities with outsiders.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SurveyOperation Desert Storm, 1991Political IssuesSecurity SystemsDisaster Planning.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>